  <body>
    <segment id="1" parent="14" relname="condition">Intuitiveness is a concept, 
and if a design goal,</segment>
    <segment id="14" parent="17" relname="span"> needs to be tested in the early phases of design. </segment>
    <segment id="3" parent="2" relname="span">
The UI part of development needs to be begin early in the lifecycle, </segment>
    <segment id="4" parent="3" relname="antithesis">
not saved for later (or never). </segment>
    <segment id="5" parent="13" relname="span">
Early testing is highly desirable over later testing. </segment>
    <segment id="6" parent="5" relname="nonvolitional-cause">
Later testing in many cases, is just too late. </segment>
    <segment id="7" parent="20" relname="nonvolitional-cause">
What developers may think is intuitive, is not at all to common users. </segment>
    <segment id="8" parent="22" relname="span">

Most of the time, &quot;intuitiveness&quot; is used to market a product. </segment>
    <segment id="9" parent="15" relname="span">
We see things like &quot;This product is intuitive.&quot; or &quot;On a scale of 1 -10, this product rates an 8 on intuitivness.&quot; </segment>
    <segment id="10" parent="19" relname="span">
These statements mean very little</segment>
    <segment id="16" parent="10" relname="volitional-cause"> because intuitiveness is not tested well or often enough. </segment>
    <segment id="11" parent="18" relname="span">
The buzz word &quot;intuitiveness&quot; is most often used to sell, not to design. </segment>
    <segment id="12" parent="11" relname="evaluation">
Big difference.</segment>
